V{{for|the English cricketer|David Makinson (cricketer)}}\u000a'''David Clement Makinson''', D.Phil, (born 27 August 1941), is an [[Australian]] mathematical [[logician]] living in [[London]], [[England]].\u000a\u000a== Career ==\u000aMakinson began his studies at [[University of Sydney|Sydney University]] in 1958 and was an associate of the [[Libertarianism|Libertarian]] Society and [[Sydney Push]]. He is a Visiting Professor in the [[London School of Economics]], [[University of London]], and an associate member of the [[Centre de Recherche en Epistémologie Appliquée]] (CREA), [[École Polytechnique]], [[Paris]]. He has held professorial rank positions in [[King's College London]], University of London and in the [[American University of Beirut]], [[Lebanon]]. From 1980 till 2001 he worked for [[UNESCO]], [[Paris]].\u000a\u000a== Contribution ==\u000aDavid Makinson is highly regarded for his work on [[belief revision]], [[Inference#Inference and uncertainty|uncertain reasoning]], and [[modal logic]]. While studying in [[Oxford University]] ([[Worcester College]]) for his [[Doctor of Philosophy|D.Phil]] under the supervision of [[Michael Dummett]], he identified the [[preface paradox]]. In belief revision he created the [[Belief revision#The AGM postulates|AGM account of theory change]] with [[Carlos Alchourrón]] and [[Peter Gärdenfors]]. In modal logic and other [[non-classical logic]]s, he showed how to establish [[completeness (logic)|completeness]] results by adapting the method of [[maximal consistent set]]. In 1969 Makinson discovered the first simple and natural [[propositional logic]] lacking the [[Kripke semantics#Finite model property|finite model property]]. Together with [[Leon van der Torre]] he developed [[input/output logic]].\u000a\u000a== External links ==\u000a* [http://david.c.makinson.googlepages.com David Makinson's website]\u000a* [http://www.crea.polytechnique.fr/ CREA],  École Polytechnique, Paris\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a{{DEFAU